<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="590" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1364,2038]" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">All the specimens examined are damaged to a greater or lesser degree, with appendages missing or damaged, but have eyes with corneas unpigmented, and much narrower than the relatively short ocular peduncles. The gastric region of the carapace is corrugated, with subtle folds and ridges.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="593" pageId="1" pageNumber="590" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1364,2038]" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">
<emphasis box="[199,470,1724,1750]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[374,470,1724,1750]" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">holotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. Integument thin and fragile. Carapace (
<figureCitation box="[944,1081,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,180,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-26@2.[166,1422,179,1292]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. carapace and cephalic appendages, lateral view; b. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; c. anterolateral carapace and eye, showing orbital margin, branchiostegal sinus, and pterygostomial spine; d. right eye, dorsal view; e. left scaphocerite, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691816/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">Fig. 1a—1c</figureCitation>
) bluntly carinate anteriorly on dorsum, with one tooth on rostrum proper anterior to level of orbital margin, with four teeth on anterior carapace. Rostrum overreaching eyes, acute at tip. Dorsal surface of gastric region of carapace with corrugated appearance, with folds and ridges. Small pterygostomial spine present. Carapace weakly sulcate laterally as shown; no hepatic spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1364,2038]" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">
Abdomen bent and twisted. Abdominal somites not dorsally carinate, without posteromesial teeth, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1340,1353,1904,1918]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">th</superScript>
somite longer than 5 
<superScript attach="none" box="[301,314,1940,1954]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">th</superScript>
. Telson (
<figureCitation box="[418,542,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="590">Fig. 2a, 2b</figureCitation>
) shallowly sulcate, with five or six pairs of dorso-lateral spines; terminating in a pair of large terminal spines (missing, but inferred from sockets) and a distally rounded spatulate endpiece with sockets for 24 smaller missing spines.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691816" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6691816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691816/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591" startId="2.[151,250,1318,1342]" targetBox="[166,1422,180,1292]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1318,1415]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,1318,1342]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">FIGURE 1</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,487,1319,1343]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei">
<emphasis box="[282,487,1319,1343]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Hymenodora chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, holotype female, CL 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. carapace and cephalic appendages, lateral view; b. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; c. anterolateral carapace and eye, showing orbital margin, branchiostegal sinus, and pterygostomial spine; d. right eye, dorsal view; e. left scaphocerite, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Eyes (
<figureCitation box="[270,419,1461,1488]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,180,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-26@2.[166,1422,179,1292]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. carapace and cephalic appendages, lateral view; b. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; c. anterolateral carapace and eye, showing orbital margin, branchiostegal sinus, and pterygostomial spine; d. right eye, dorsal view; e. left scaphocerite, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691816/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Figs. 1b—1d</figureCitation>
) with corneas unpigmented, narrower than ocular peduncle. Cornea set laterally at end of peduncle; peduncle short, nearly as long as broad at base, with large pointed tubercle at inner distal end overreaching cornea.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Scaphocerite (
<figureCitation box="[359,438,1569,1595]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[166,1422,180,1292]" captionTargetId="figure-26@2.[166,1422,179,1292]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. carapace and cephalic appendages, lateral view; b. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; c. anterolateral carapace and eye, showing orbital margin, branchiostegal sinus, and pterygostomial spine; d. right eye, dorsal view; e. left scaphocerite, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691816" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691816/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 1e</figureCitation>
) narrowing distally, truncate at tip, distolateral spine reaching beyond end, without teeth proximal to distolateral spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Mandibles with incisor process toothed along entire opposable margins, molar process of right mandible (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
) with transverse distal surface triangular, compressed and sub-linear on left (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1125,1677,1704]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" box="[199,931,1713,1739]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Palp of first maxilla (
<figureCitation box="[438,518,1713,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 2e</figureCitation>
) with large spine on median surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" box="[199,1175,1749,1776]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Second maxilla (
<figureCitation box="[388,465,1749,1776]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 2f</figureCitation>
) with proximal endite lacking papilla and submarginal lamella.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" box="[199,1130,1785,1811]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
First maxilliped (
<figureCitation box="[393,474,1785,1811]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[445,474,1785,1811]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="591" unit="g" value="2.0">2g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
) with slender central lobe with only one transverse suture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">
Second maxilliped (
<figureCitation box="[427,510,1821,1848]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-15@3.[165,1422,181,1885]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Hymenodora chacei, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Fig. 2h</figureCitation>
) with distal segment somewhat ovoid, attached diagonally to preceding segment; epipod without podobranch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" box="[199,1013,1893,1919]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Exopods of third maxillipeds and pereopods neither foliaceous nor rigid.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" box="[199,1131,1929,1955]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">Third maxillipeds extending anteriorly slightly beyond distal end of antennal scale.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1461,2027]" pageId="2" pageNumber="591">First through fourth pereopods incomplete; fifth pereopods reaching anteriorly to one-half the length of antennal scale.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691824" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6691824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691824/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="592" startId="3.[151,250,1909,1933]" targetBox="[165,1422,182,1885]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1909,2041]" pageId="3" pageNumber="592">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,1909,1933]" pageId="3" pageNumber="592">FIGURE 2</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="2022" box="[281,485,1909,1933]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="3" pageNumber="592" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei">
<emphasis box="[281,485,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="592">Hymenodora chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, holotype female, CL. 25 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21317); a. telson, dorsal view; b. distal end of telson, dorsal view; c. left mandible (flexor or dorsal view); d. right mandible (flexor or dorsal view); e. left first maxilla, setae not shown; f. left second maxilla, setae not shown; g. left first maxilliped, setae not shown; h. left second maxilliped, setae not shown.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691826" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6691826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691826/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" startId="4.[151,250,1225,1249]" targetBox="[177,1410,181,1201]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1225,1286]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,270,1225,1249]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">FIGURE 3</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="2022" box="[283,489,1225,1249]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei">
<emphasis box="[283,489,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Hymenodora chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, paratype female, CL 18 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21319); a. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; b. right eye, dorsal view, tubercle broken.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1331,2042]" box="[199,836,1331,1358]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis box="[199,264,1331,1357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Color</emphasis>
. Color in life not known; colorless in preservative.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1331,2042]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis box="[199,311,1368,1393]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Variation.</emphasis>
The number of teeth on the anterior dorsal region of the carapace and on the rostrum proper of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wasmer, 2022" authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,380,1403,1429]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[151,380,1403,1429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Hymenodora chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[389,451,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
varies: a 
<specimenCount box="[566,587,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<typeStatus box="[596,695,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">paratype</typeStatus>
, CL 18.0 mm (
<collectionCode box="[871,958,1404,1430]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34802" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34802" name="Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="Museum">LACM</collectionCode>
: 
<collectionCode box="[962,1051,1404,1430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">DISCO</collectionCode>
:21329), has a total of seven teeth (three rostral and four on the anterior dorsal carapace (
<figureCitation box="[749,850,1439,1466]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1225,1249]" captionTargetBox="[177,1410,181,1201]" captionTargetId="figure-26@4.[177,1410,181,1201]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Hymenodora chacei, paratype female, CL 18 mm, (LACM:DISCO:21319); a. carapace and eyes, dorsal view; b. right eye, dorsal view, tubercle broken." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691826/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Fig.3a, b</figureCitation>
); a 
<specimenCount box="[888,909,1440,1466]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
<typeStatus box="[914,1013,1440,1466]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">paratype</typeStatus>
, CL 10.0 mm (
<collectionCode box="[1175,1261,1440,1466]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34802" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34802" name="Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="Museum">LACM</collectionCode>
: 
<collectionCode box="[1264,1352,1440,1466]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">DISCO</collectionCode>
:21320) has no teeth on the rostrum proper and two on the anterior dorsal carapace (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1121,1475,1502]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1966,1990]" captionTargetBox="[312,1276,874,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-293@5.[312,1276,874,1943]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hymenodora chacei, paratype female, CL 10 mm. (LACM:DISCO:21320; a. carapace and eyes, lateral view; b. anterior carapace and eyes, dorsal view; c. right eye, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6691830" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6691830/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Fig. 4a, b</figureCitation>
). All of the 
<typeStatus box="[1257,1364,1476,1502]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">paratypes</typeStatus>
either have no telsons, or telsons missing the distal portion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1331,2042]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis box="[199,344,1547,1573]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[617,665,1548,1574]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">type</typeStatus>
locality in the central North Pacific (
<geoCoordinate box="[1109,1171,1548,1574]" degrees="31" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" precision="55555" value="31.0">31°N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1186,1267,1547,1574]" degrees="159" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" precision="55555" value="-159.0">159°W</geoCoordinate>
) at a depth of 
<quantity box="[151,239,1584,1610]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" unit="m" value="4200.0">4200 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1331,2042]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis box="[199,325,1619,1645]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Etymology.</emphasis>
It gives me great pleasure to name this species in honor of the late Zoologist Emeritus in the Department of Invertebrate Zoology, National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, Dr. Fenner A. Chace, Jr. (1908—2004), who was “one of the most influential carcinologists of the 20 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1125,1138,1691,1705]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">th</superScript>
century” (
<bibRefCitation author="Lemaitre, R." pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="621 - 639" refId="ref5319" refString="Lemaitre, R. (2005) Remarks on the life and works of Fenner A. Chace, Jr. (1908 - 2004), with a list of his taxa and complete bibliography. Crustaceana, 78 (5), 621 - 639. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 156854005774318141" type="journal article" year="2005">Lemaitre, 2005: 622</bibRefCitation>
). His taxonomic work on caridean shrimps, and particularly on the oplophorid shrimps (
<bibRefCitation author="Chace, F. A. Jr." box="[1213,1360,1727,1753]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="24 - 31" refId="ref4884" refString="Chace, F. A. Jr. (1936) Revision of the bathypelagic prawns of the Family Acanthephyridae, with notes on a new Family, Gomphonotidae. Journal of the Washington Academy of Sciences, 26 (1), 24 - 31." type="journal article" year="1936">Chace, 1936</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chace, F. A. Jr." box="[1373,1432,1728,1754]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="117 - 209" refId="ref4931" refString="Chace, F. A. Jr. (1940) Plankton of the Bermuda Oceanographic Expeditions, IX: The Bathypelagic Caridean Crustacea. Zoologica, 25 (2), 117 - 209. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / p. 184703" type="journal article" year="1940">1940</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chace, F. A. Jr." box="[151,210,1764,1790]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="1 - 51" refId="ref4979" refString="Chace, F. A. Jr. (1947) The deep-sea prawns of the Family Oplophoridae in the Bingham Oceanographic Collection. Bulletin of the Bingham Oceanographic Collection, 11 (1), 1 - 51." type="journal article" year="1947">1947</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chace, F. A. Jr." box="[221,278,1763,1790]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="1 - 82" refId="ref5019" refString="Chace, F. A. Jr. (1986) The caridean shrimps (Crustacea: Decapoda) of the Albratross Philippine Expedition, 1907 - 1910, Part 4: Oplophoridae and Nematocarcinidae. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 432, 1 - 82. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.432" type="journal article" year="1986">1986</bibRefCitation>
) did much to further our understanding of this family of shrimps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="594" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1331,2042]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="594" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis box="[199,297,1799,1825]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Remarks</emphasis>
. While Dr. Chace’s taxonomic work was voluminous, he early on coauthored several papers on the eye structure of bathypelagic caridean shrimps (Welsh &amp; Chace, 1937, 1938). It is unfortunate that he did not live to make any comments about the reduced eyes of 
<taxonomicName authority="Wasmer, 2022" authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="2022" box="[782,1010,1871,1897]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chacei" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[782,1010,1871,1897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Hymenodora chacei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1020,1082,1872,1898]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
I found him willing to answer questions in 1966 when I was an unknown graduate student at a small college in eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[1158,1291,1907,1933]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Washington</collectingRegion>
where I was working on midwater shrimps for a Masters dissertation, through my doctoral work at 
<collectingRegion box="[1158,1308,1944,1970]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Oregon State</collectingRegion>
University where I described a new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", G. O. Sars" authorityYear="1877" box="[565,711,1979,2005]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[565,711,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Hymenodora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, (
<taxonomicName authority="Wasmer, 1972" authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="1972" box="[737,1120,1979,2006]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Hymenodora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acanthetelsonis">
<emphasis box="[737,947,1979,2005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">H. acanthetelsonis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wasmer, R. A." box="[957,1120,1980,2006]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" pagination="87 - 91" refId="ref6020" refString="Wasmer, R. A. (1972) A new species of Hymenodora (Decapoda, Oplophoridae) from the Northwestern Pacific. Crustaceana, 22 (1), 87 - 91. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 156854072 X 00705" type="journal article" year="1972">Wasmer, 1972</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
) and finally as a university professor in suburban 
<collectingRegion box="[403,539,2015,2041]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Washington</collectingRegion>
, D. C., where I found him always willing to review manuscripts for me, and to visit when I came down to the museum on other business. I especially appreciate his helpful suggestion about where in the crustacean collections of the USNM I might find additional specimens of a new species of the shrimp genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Spence Bate" authorityYear="1888" box="[151,282,223,249]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Systellaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="594" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,282,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="594">Systellaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="Wasmer, 1986" authorityName="Wasmer" authorityYear="1986" box="[300,698,223,249]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Systellaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="594" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eltanini">
<emphasis box="[300,526,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="594">Systellaspis eltanini</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Wasmer, R. A." box="[535,698,223,249]" pageId="5" pageNumber="594" pagination="29 - 68" refId="ref6067" refString="Wasmer, R. A. (1986) Pelagic shrimps of the family Oplophoridae (Crustacea: Decapoda) from the Pacific sector of the Southern Ocean: USNS Eltanin Cruises 10, 11, 14 - 16, 19 - 21, 24, and 25. In: Kornicker, L. S. (Ed.), Biology of the Antarctic Seas XVII, Antarctic Research Series, Washington, 44, pp. 29 - 68. https: // doi. org / 10.1029 / AR 044 p 0029" type="journal article" year="1986">Wasmer, 1986</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[698,707,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="594">)</emphasis>
when I was working on oplophorid shrimps from the Southern Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
